SmartFi Wallet Sweep and Custody Flow Analysis
Executive Summary
Our review of SmartFi’s transaction activity shows a recurring operational pattern: customers deposited cryptocurrency into individual user wallets, and SmartFi’s system then attempted to move those assets into omnibus company-controlled wallets. The user wallets appear to have functioned as temporary receiving addresses rather than separate long-term storage accounts for each customer. This pattern was observed across multiple assets, including USDT and USDC, and across multiple customer accounts.
Transaction Flow Overview
1. Customer Deposit	2. User Wallet	3. Gas Station Funding	4. Sweep Attempt	5. Omnibus Wallet
Customer sends USDT, USDC, or another supported asset.	The asset lands in an individual user wallet that functions as a temporary receiving address.	SmartFi’s Gas Station sends ETH or BNB so the wallet can pay blockchain transaction fees.	SmartFi’s system attempts to move, or “sweep,” the asset out of the user wallet.	The asset is moved, or intended to be moved, into SmartFi’s omnibus wallet structure.
