Observed Custody and Sweep Activity
A key observation is that, with limited exceptions identified in the reviewed data, asset transfers were sent or attempted to be sent to a destination labeled “HOTWALLET.” For consistency with prior communications, this report refers to that destination as SmartFi’s omnibus wallet. An omnibus wallet is a centralized platform wallet used to hold or move assets operationally, including assets associated with multiple users. In the reviewed examples where transfers to the omnibus wallet were completed, later wallet balance records showed that the original user wallet no longer held the deposited asset. This supports the conclusion that the reviewed activity reflects movement of customer assets out of user wallets and into an omnibus custody structure.
The data also shows repeated funding from a source labeled “Gas Station.” Gas refers to the blockchain transaction fee required to move assets. On Ethereum, those fees are paid in ETH; on Binance Smart Chain, they are typically paid in BNB. The Gas Station appears to have supplied small amounts of ETH or BNB to user wallets so SmartFi could pay the required network fees and complete asset transfers. SmartFi’s Gas Station appears to have funded user wallets with ETH specifically so ERC-20 tokens, such as USDT, could be swept from those user wallets into SmartFi’s omnibus wallet. The recurrence of Gas Station funding across the reviewed wallets supports the conclusion that this was a centralized operational process rather than separate customer-directed activity.
Sweep Cycle Analysis Methodology
To evaluate whether balances remained in user wallets because SmartFi intended to keep assets segregated, or because sweep activity failed or was delayed, we performed a Sweep Cycle Analysis using the transaction ledger. The analysis reconstructed the lifecycle of deposited assets by linking the original customer deposit, the first failed sweep attempt, the last failed sweep attempt, and any later successful transfer to SmartFi’s omnibus wallet. This approach allowed us to assess the timing of sweep attempts after deposit, the number and duration of failed attempts, retry behavior, and whether the assets were ultimately moved into omnibus custody.
The Sweep Cycle Analysis showed a recurring operational pattern in the reviewed population. In the examples reviewed, SmartFi attempted to sweep customer assets shortly after the original deposit. Where the initial transfer failed, SmartFi’s system continued trying to move the assets into omnibus custody, often at regular intervals of approximately five to six minutes. The repeated timing is consistent with automated retry logic rather than separate manual customer activity.
Representative User Timeline
One representative example is USER 110562. The records show that USER 110562 deposited 75 USDT on November 18, 2021, followed shortly afterward by a 0.008 ETH transfer from Gas Station. SmartFi’s system then began attempting to move the 75 USDT from the user wallet to the omnibus wallet, with the first failed sweep attempt occurring approximately one minute after the deposit. The ledger reflects 5,831 failed attempts before the assets were ultimately swept on December 10, 2021. The repeated timing, same asset amount, same destination, same fee-related error condition, and eventual successful sweep are consistent with an automated operational process. The temporary presence of funds in the user wallet therefore appears more likely to be a processing exception than evidence that the funds were intentionally held separately for that customer.
