Broader Sweep Analysis Observations
The broader sweep analysis identified the same pattern across additional users in the reviewed population. For example, USER 551916 deposited USDT on September 27, 2021, experienced failed sweep activity within minutes of the deposit, and was ultimately swept on October 19, 2021 after more than 5,900 failed attempts. Other long-duration failed sweep cycles included USER 515531, which experienced more than 20,000 failed sweep attempts before being swept on October 23, 2023; USER 623281, which experienced approximately 14,000 failed attempts before eventual sweep activity; and USER 613740, which experienced more than 12,000 failed attempts before being swept. Although the number of retries and the duration varied, the common pattern in these examples was that SmartFi’s systems repeatedly attempted to move the assets into omnibus custody before ultimately succeeding.
The analysis also identified batch-resolution events, where multiple previously failed sweep cycles were resolved at nearly identical timestamps across unrelated users. For example, multiple user wallets, including USER 151256, USER 551916, USER 909050, USER 788102, and USER 440136, were ultimately swept at approximately 05:38 AM UTC on October 19, 2021. A similar pattern occurred on December 10, 2021, when multiple user wallets, including USER 613740, USER 736100, USER 706174, USER 739434, USER 698490, USER 807276, and USER 110562, were swept within seconds of one another at approximately 07:17 AM UTC. Additional clustering was observed on February 5, 2022 and October 23, 2023. These synchronized sweep events are consistent with centralized processing activity rather than user-specific action.
A smaller exception population was classified as “Failed Attempts Only,” meaning the available sweep-cycle analysis did not identify a corresponding successful sweep event within the reviewed data. Examples included USER 437263, USER 902233, USER 478432, USER 527192, and USER 118370. Even within this exception population, however, the transaction history reflected repeated efforts by SmartFi’s systems to transfer assets into omnibus custody. These exceptions therefore do not, by themselves, demonstrate an intent to maintain segregated customer custody and should be reviewed against the full ledger, transaction history, and vault balance population.
Taken together, the transaction records, Gas Station funding, sweep-cycle timing, failed and successful sweep attempts, batch-resolution events, transfers to the omnibus wallet, and later wallet balances support a consistent operating model in the reviewed data: customer assets were moved, or repeatedly attempted to be moved, from user wallets into SmartFi-controlled omnibus wallets, with limited exceptions requiring further ledger review. The reviewed activity does not support a model where each customer’s assets were consistently maintained in separate, customer-specific wallets. Where assets temporarily remained in user wallets, the records commonly show fee-related failures, repeated automated retry attempts, delayed batch resolution, or exception cases requiring further review, rather than evidence of an intended segregated custody model.
Evidence Summary
1. Customer deposits were repeatedly moved or attempted to be moved toward omnibus wallets
•	The records repeatedly show the same basic sequence:
o	Customer deposit into a user wallet.
o	User wallet transfer, or attempted transfer, to the omnibus wallet.
•	This pattern appears across multiple users and asset types, which supports a platform-wide operating model.
2. User wallets often did not retain the deposited asset after a successful sweep
After successful sweep activity in the reviewed examples, later balance records showed that the original user wallet no longer held the deposited asset.
•	This indicates that the asset had been moved out of the originating wallet.
3. Assets from different customers converged into the same custody structure
With limited exceptions identified in the reviewed data, transfers from user wallets were directed, or attempted to be directed, to a destination labeled HOTWALLET, referred to in this report as SmartFi’s omnibus wallet.
Movement of assets from multiple user wallets into a common omnibus wallet structure supports a commingling analysis rather than a customer-by-customer segregation model.
4. Gas Station funding appears centrally managed
Multiple user wallets received ETH or BNB from the same source labeled Gas Station.
•	This recurring pattern suggests that SmartFi centrally funded wallets so its system could pay transaction fees and move customer assets.
•	SmartFi’s Gas Station appears to have funded the user wallets with ETH specifically so ERC-20 tokens, such as USDT, could be swept from those user wallets into SmartFi’s omnibus wallet.
5. Repeated sweep failures indicate automated retry behavior
•	Multiple failed sweeps used the same error message: “INSUFFICIENT_FUNDS_FOR_FEE.”
The attempts repeated at predictable intervals in the reviewed examples, commonly around every five to six minutes.
•	This timing pattern is consistent with an automated system process rather than one-off manual customer activity.
•	The failed attempts show that SmartFi’s system was still trying to move the assets; they do not show that SmartFi intended to leave those assets segregated.
6. Failed sweeps were often followed by successful transfers
In the reviewed examples, repeated failed attempts were followed by a successful movement of assets to the omnibus wallet.
•	This supports the conclusion that failures were processing exceptions, not evidence of a customer-specific custody model.
7. Fee currency was supplied and later reduced
•	Some user wallets received ETH or BNB from Gas Station, and later balance records showed lower amounts remaining.
•	This is consistent with the fee currency being used to support later transaction activity.
8. The reviewed data does not show consistent customer-specific segregation
The same deposit, funding, sweep, retry, and omnibus-wallet transfer pattern appears across multiple customers in the reviewed data.
•	Based on the reviewed records, there is no clear evidence that the assets reviewed were consistently excluded from SmartFi’s broader aggregation process.
9. Timing analysis supports a system-controlled process
•	Customer deposits were commonly followed by sweep activity within a short period of time.
•	Failed sweeps often repeated at predictable intervals of approximately five to six minutes.
•	That regularity is more consistent with scheduled system logic than individual customer action.
